[{"id":30539,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c0fcae87-d21a-4600-8e26-69cde9647a79-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 66px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a55177ff-6c08-47cc-a64f-d0788a79fb96-image.png\" style=\"width: 118px; height: 69px;\" />","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HC</mi><mo>&#8801;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#8801;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/96156992-18b0-42c9-bfe3-12e5b8f87b5a-image.png\" style=\"width: 358px; height: 94px;\" /></p><p>As <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math> compound given positive Tollen&#39;s test hence it may consist&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>CHO</mi></math> (aldehyde group)&nbsp;or it can be&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCOOH</mi></math></p><p>So for the given option :</p><p>(3)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#8801;</mo><mi>CH</mi><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mi>Ozonolysis</mi></mover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>+</mo><munder><mi>HCOOH</mi><munder><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi>ve</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>tollen</mi><mo>&#39;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>test</mi></mrow></munder></munder></math></p><p>and for other compounds (options):</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/56631473-10b9-47a1-8ba8-3b6c13db77e2-image.png\" style=\"width: 602px; height: 213px;\" /></p><p>(3)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#8801;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mi>Ozonolysis</mi></mover><munder><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>COOH</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>Does</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>not</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>show</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>tollen</mi><mo>&#39;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>test</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></munder></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30622,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{o-}$Nitrophenol is more volatile in steam than those of $\\mathrm{m}-$ and $\\mathrm{p}-$ isomers","$\\mathrm{o-}$Nitrophenol shows Intramolecular $\\mathrm{H}-$ bonding","$\\mathrm{o-}$ Nitrophenol shows Intermolecular $\\mathrm{H}-$ bonding","Melting point of $\\mathrm{o-}$Nitrophenol is lower than those of $\\mathrm{m}-$ and $\\mathrm{p}-$ isomers."],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/geYfbjad8EspSgUTvoKNyM3CfeuScfm7M-ZYH5MFO74.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nIntramolecular $\\mathrm{H}$-bonding decreases water solubility.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (Offline)","image":null},{"id":30524,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>III</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>IV</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Only in&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0dabeb1a-fc69-4272-a42a-af522ecbe520-image.png\" style=\"width: 149px; height: 107px;\" />&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;can be substituted by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;combine with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Ag</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;to form a yellow precipitate&nbsp;of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgI</mi></math>. While</p><p>in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>II</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>III</mi></math> substitution reaction is not possible due to partial double bond character.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30586,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7428337b-4e32-438b-a366-b13e2ced2aa4-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 158px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/910caa98-a923-47b9-821a-6b726b20542f-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 135px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/315dc68d-20e1-4d14-afc1-7f15af387bf0-image.png\" style=\"width: 230px; height: 140px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9dc6c958-6621-4d60-894f-4438171f5930-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 168px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/efd59bea-8d63-4a99-8f6c-1260291a9c39-image45.png\"> <br/><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/38944159-1507-402a-96d7-cb40a09fe45a-image46.png\"> <br/>This reaction is Friedel-craft-acylation, <math><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></math> group is an ortho and para directing.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30562,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1390ca8a-8752-438a-bc22-693cd9e1d5ee-image.png\" style=\"width: 163px; height: 78px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dbe5d9b1-e71a-43f5-8c1e-bd9e3d02ca41-image.png\" style=\"width: 174px; height: 83px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0f934a48-b40d-4922-9dc5-f661ac7c44f3-image.png\" style=\"width: 146px; height: 100px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8cf2c753-3f69-4d7e-b067-b85f3b126fb6-image.png\" style=\"width: 107px; height: 98px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/377e0598-9ac0-4b57-a024-8359bc8f8125-image.png\" style=\"width: 456px; height: 161px;\" />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30480,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>A substitution reaction is a chemical reaction during which one functional group in a chemical compound is replaced by another functional group.The number of different substitution products possible when ethane is allowed to react with bromine in sunlight are <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>sunlight</mi></mover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Br</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Br</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Br</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Br</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CHBr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CHBr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CHBr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CHBr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Br</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CHBr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p></blockquote><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math>&nbsp;Bromine atoms:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;product possible</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math> Bromine atoms : <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> product possible</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math> Bromine atoms : <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> products possible</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> Bromine atoms : <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> products possible</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> Bromine atoms : <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> products possible</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> Bromine atom : <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;product possible</p><p>Total <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn></math> products possible</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30497,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["&#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&#39; and &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&#39; are both Markovnikov addition products.","&#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&#39; is Markovnikov product and &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&#39; is antiMarkovnikov product.","&#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&#39; and &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&#39; are both anti-Markovnikov products.","&#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&#39; is Markovnikov and &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&#39; is anti-<br />Markovnikov product."],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>In the first step of hydroboration oxidation, the boron and hydrogen add to the same face of the double&nbsp;bond. In the second step, the OH takes the identical position occupied by the&nbsp;boron. Thus, the OH and H groups that are effectively added to the original&nbsp;double bond are cis. The overall addition takes place in anti Markovnikov&#39;s fashion.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/de84a424-c210-4858-beed-5f72dbc0ff5c-image.png\" style=\"width: 337px; height: 104px;\" /></p><p>The reagent is mercury(II) acetate, which dissociates slightly to form <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi>Hg</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>OAc</mi><mo>)</mo></math>.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi>Hg</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>OAc</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is the electrophile that adds to the pi bond. &bull; The intermediate is a three-membered ring called the mercurinium ion. Overall, the addition of water follows Markovnikov&rsquo;s rule</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5904aa24-215d-4fed-813f-437aea1279d6-e608ab7c-55ed-4f21-8315-c86bd214ce49-image.png\" style=\"width: 611px; height: 229px;\" /></p><p>The reaction does not suffer from rearrangements because there is no carbocation intermediate.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30505,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>and dil.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mn>273</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>,(dilute), <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>273</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>Zn</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>Zn</mi></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cdefb8ca-6cfb-4431-be57-306b2e23aee9-8525a8ca-bf38-4117-8ee9-7d0ffa5ab1ed-image.png\" style=\"width: 728px; height: 294px;\" /></p><p>The substance produce by ants is formic acid, which is the product of oxidation of &quot;a&quot;, means &#39;a&#39; should be formaldehyde. Now, formaldehyde and ketons are prepared by reductive&nbsp;ozonolysis of alkenes. And by oxidation in presence of strong oxidising agents alkenes give ketons and acids.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30443,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct","Both Statement I and Statement II are correct","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{C} \\equiv \\mathrm{CH}+\\mathrm{Na} \\rightarrow \\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{C} \\equiv \\mathrm{C}^{-} \\mathrm{Na}^{+}+\\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{H}_2$\n\nStatement-l is correct.\nMoles of $\\mathrm{C}_3 \\mathrm{H}_4=\\frac{4}{40}=0.1$ mole\n$\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{C} \\equiv \\mathrm{CH}+\\mathrm{NaNH}_2 \\rightarrow \\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{C} \\equiv \\mathrm{C}^{-} \\mathrm{Na}^{+}+\\mathrm{NH}_3$\n0.1 mole\n0.1 mole\n\nVolume of $\\mathrm{NH}_3=(0.1)(22.4)=2.24 \\mathrm{~L}$\nStatement-II is incorrect.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30626,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["mixture of $o-$ and p-bromotoluenes","mixture of $o-$ and p-dibromobenzenes","mixture of $\\mathrm{o}$ - and p-bromoanilines","mixture of 0 - and $\\mathrm{m}$-bromotoluenes"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/tVH0Z-BiCO1w4jt8zRXFMiKsPsOaZSEfYTVU4v1nxhA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":30551,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/809eb13b-6681-4aa4-9bb4-365499021ea8-image.png\" style=\"width: 347px; height: 100px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/686eb3da-965f-43de-b71a-d1e3f3d7c3a5-image.png\" style=\"width: 347px; height: 97px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ad49dd82-a9ee-427a-bf80-8e4001bd233d-image.png\" style=\"width: 347px; height: 100px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/33302f4e-da37-4d8b-a949-29f7eb54f76c-image.png\" style=\"width: 582px; height: 64px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b501b38c-f487-4b27-bf29-8b2cb8456b33-0a581093-35b9-4af4-8484-6d0af7b4662b-image.png\" style=\"width: 383px; height: 299px;\" /></p><p>Syn hydroxylation takes place with cold KMnO<sub>4</sub>. CrO<sub>3</sub>&nbsp;convert secondary alcohol into ketone and&nbsp;tertiary alcohol remains unaffected.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30627,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CHO}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCH}_3$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COCH}_3$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CHO}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/QcH05vgydliCY9e81BFRqYcLeIGRTaHT3apJFmWcYzQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":30408,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["C and A Only","B and C Only","A and D Only","B and D Only"],"answer":1,"solution":"Presence of $NO_2$ group in Benzene ring deactivate ring towards electrophilic substitution reaction due to $-M$ effective & activate ring towards nucleophilic substitution.<br>So, B & C are correct.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30510,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a9803c33-7c46-49f6-ad8c-8306f000bd76-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 127px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7dd92e9e-6c15-4216-8edc-ef3d90b66728-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 134px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/91f8bf99-41ab-4372-8021-1f6803d3a45e-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 121px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6c897a0e-21fd-4858-b617-1bcb2ab6d1f2-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 132px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Electrophile will attack at ortho and Para position with respect to better Electron releasing group(ERG)</p><p>ERG : &ndash; OH &gt; &ndash; CH<sub>3</sub></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1dc288b3-99fb-4f32-bb07-34b8d2828c64-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 134px;\" /></p><p>Para position with respect to group <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>OH</mi></math>&nbsp;group&nbsp;and it will be meta position with respect to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> group.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30485,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A is false but R is true","A is true but R is false","Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Clemmensen reduction: The carbonyl group of aldehydes and ketones is reduced to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;group on treatment with zinc-amalgam and concentrated hydrochloric acid.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/91fee4df-c1da-444d-b3c6-fd19cfa37c31-9896024.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 124px;\" /></p><p>The acid sensitive alcohol group reacts with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi></math>, hence Clemmenson reduction is not suitable for above conversion.</p><p>So, assertion is false but reason is true.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30453,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Monochlorination means the substitution of a chlorine. When chlorine atom is added to the below structure, chlorine will substitute at one of the hydrogen.</p><p>Mono chlorination of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-methyl butane gives four structural isomers.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5641f60d-8e46-4590-870c-9e90204e6a58.png\" style=\"width: 649px; height: 188px;\"/></p><p>Here only two, i.e., I and III are optically active. Since each optically active compound has two enantiomers, therefore, total six isomeric compounds are possible.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30441,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A-II, B-I, C-III, D-IV","A-II, B-III, C-I, D-IV","A-IV, B-I, C-III, D-II","A-IV, B-III, C-I, D-II"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b8ml032qED3Zu_BKPCSUXgX7gdEsraGDDTQYWJq-rHQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30538,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ecc16ce7-9e32-4adf-ab0f-b18feda4b01b-image.png\" style=\"width: 161px; height: 140px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a8d1671c-1405-4728-b787-9d100688a1ab-image.png\" style=\"width: 148px; height: 134px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c5822d65-684d-4305-a3dc-e5150dd5dd52-image.png\" style=\"width: 177px; height: 147px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/053c3870-8160-4ec5-87d7-f3db2d4e4a68-image.png\" style=\"width: 185px; height: 113px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img height=\"235\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f901bec6-311c-4e51-adf9-3b6005ae3e2a-image.png\" style=\"float: left;\" width=\"615\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30439,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/TX3oWC0uWWLAYtfePjrbBoWnW53l_nx1Nf60AIu9vPg.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0r6SBkkt6--6ZD6OC6PA_YUYiQc3jK59OoYdp_xj_2o.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/NbcE6awM3COwQGJOgsx66WlM3SnxrUUaQFx3tGIil3c.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9F-I-4vldcfslHWn0OBZM6SJDT5K0Q9Sffaw2hXC-qQ.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/LztD3iwui9V3iJ-ANi0A9YptjX8-0MKx0xp6tNhBjKQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (24 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30451,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["\\(\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}, \\mathrm{H}^{+}\\)and \\(\\mathrm{KMnO}_4\\)","\\(\\mathrm{O}_3, \\mathrm{Zn} / \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}\\) and \\(\\mathrm{NaOH}_{(\\text {alc) }} / \\mathrm{I}_2\\)","\\(\\mathrm{O}_3, \\mathrm{Zn} / \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}\\) and \\(\\mathrm{KMnO}_4\\)","\\(\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}, \\mathrm{H}^{+}\\)and \\(\\mathrm{NaOH}_{(\\mathrm{alc})} / \\mathrm{I}_2\\)"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/nkBLIW6MBikANwzX2grKoRSR54hhLWad1sIIntg9GtQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30520,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bb5cfb34-449b-4ae8-822a-c7eb9d90836b-image.png\" style=\"width: 215px; height: 102px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/81da926f-8bef-4106-870f-0405751867b8-image.png\" style=\"width: 287px; height: 145px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b6c1622a-585a-47df-b8f0-9a4a5e88551b-image.png\" style=\"width: 347px; height: 111px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/34c4e824-21b6-47eb-aa90-1d078dab2e23-image.png\" style=\"width: 302px; height: 106px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/64921b98-b40c-46cc-a0b0-7d47bf17b484-9eca4ddc-c6f5-4a68-9940-559be6120830-image.png\" style=\"width: 689px; height: 147px;\" /></p><p>Major product will be formed by elimination reaction. Product having conjugated double bonds is more stable.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30521,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/78cbe25f-0595-40d8-9ddf-152fb9614413-image.png\" style=\"width: 377px; height: 103px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1f2073f3-edfd-4721-87c0-57b200a652a0-image.png\" style=\"width: 349px; height: 105px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b14e4fb4-8c39-4cef-9bcb-e2a4d114e132-image.png\" style=\"width: 371px; height: 109px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5aa8ed1d-e04c-4dac-98a5-4719a2d9201e-image.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 106px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e9f405e9-1ce3-407c-b035-efc8d2d9a769-9e9c5c98-0c3a-4488-b703-0a6be5dd5431-image.png\" style=\"width: 777px; height: 145px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30415,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["B and D Only","A and C Only","A and B Only","B and C Only"],"answer":0,"solution":"But-2-yne ($CH_3-C\\equiv C-CH_3$) undergoes partial hydrogenation.<br>Reaction with $Pd/C$ (Lindlar-like conditions for 1 mole $H_2$) gives cis-but-2-ene as product $X$.<br>Reaction with $Na/liq. NH_3$ (Birch reduction) gives trans-but-2-ene as product $Y$.<br>Statement A: $X$ (cis) and $Y$ (trans) are geometrical isomers, hence stereoisomers. This is correct.<br>Statement B: Cis-but-2-ene ($X$) has a non-zero dipole moment ($\\mu \\neq 0$) due to the additive nature of bond moments, while trans-but-2-ene ($Y$) has zero dipole moment ($\\mu = 0$) due to symmetry. Thus, statement B is incorrect.<br>Statement C: Cis-isomers generally have higher boiling points than trans-isomers due to higher dipole-dipole interactions. So, B.P. of $X > Y$. This is correct.<br>Statement D: Reductive ozonolysis ($O_3/Zn, H_2O$) of both cis-but-2-ene and trans-but-2-ene yields the same product, ethanal ($CH_3CHO$). Thus, statement D is incorrect.<br>The incorrect statements are B and D.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30437,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4R4fQqVx6s-P2AJzmz8-vRdjlsWhxtSljnV2CZ0C6JI.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/mXPwchckLmh4iVX1XcKLZLoc04g4mX4rJ6GUFoZhLnc.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/YfHQ_Ap8BnaR2HT8-IfAG0TvxcN7Ms52Sl873iknZj4.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/MsvkywBScmrxoixNhv9x4lE-j9Tu6aKB-f23l9ZWr50.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/MwK0-aDoFIGQQs72c8swe3JRcQ9rMYO5G5xw7rjUtwE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30528,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/46dfeb45-3aad-464d-9ce2-bad7ce042e28-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 157px;\" /></p><p>ENT denote enantiomer of product.</p><p>The total number of products possible <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30593,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"93\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/93fe27ce-09ce-4a2f-a968-3621f559e37c-image.png\" width=\"182\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"123\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f344dc67-5c51-40fc-a7cb-3eab6798d417-image.png\" width=\"127\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b0058bac-6f29-425e-8b86-e95d3548c532-61f18e57-7060-4a94-a630-0a661010fea7-image.png\" style=\"width: 185px; height: 75px;\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"71\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1f21a3b9-b718-4cbf-8f39-7b922b85f202-image.png\" width=\"208\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Addition of alc. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KOH</mi></math> to haloalkanes follows the Saytzeff rule which points towards greater stability. Saytzeff&#39;s rule implies that elimination reactions favour formation of alkene with greater number of substituents.<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/def9c059-c492-4e0a-8e19-5ed7876d30bf-61f18e57-7060-4a94-a630-0a661010fea7-image.png\" style=\"width: 185px; height: 75px;\" /><br /><br />Not only that, but it also gives the molecule an extended conjugate system which further enhances its stability.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30629,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["$$\n\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}=\\mathrm{CH}_2\n$$","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/KRPXp_TkphCazr7H9yEr2jNZFiE-5S9qpd_lYiM57uY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Dc0lVbEuYkXjGp6WbyakTvfu_4yd-_9VAd4hBqFgJsI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/S3ibB88brnGNsS02Sc8gbE7a1Bd4sp4HTAUr06_FZ0I.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{MgX}+\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{C} \\equiv \\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{H} \\longrightarrow \\mathrm{CH}_4$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":30438,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["2-Phenylhepta-2,5-diene","6-Phenylhepta-2,4-diene","6-Phenylhepta-3,5-diene","2-Phenylhepta-2,4-diene"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/zBAZFjZspApopTe6PgUD8IsRab0dIAtfbkqTtKuGyVA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30554,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d50912b0-2eeb-416d-9ffe-384ba2afade5-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 100px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/30be0ad9-1b44-4b2a-9e08-78d2eb315b94-image.png\" style=\"width: 280px; height: 64px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a78b7933-92a2-45d9-85aa-9bbd7cf4b350-image.png\" style=\"width: 240px; height: 90px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1cfb936a-aea3-4f65-9fd5-eb9a3fde50f7-image.png\" style=\"width: 190px; height: 120px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6f1b8130-5ec7-4ebe-832c-7b2ffbe94338-image.png\" style=\"width: 411px; height: 230px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30397,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["C > A > B > D","C > A > D > B","B > D > A > C","A > B > C > D"],"answer":0,"solution":"The stability of alkenes is directly proportional to the number of $\\alpha$-hydrogen atoms due to hyperconjugation.<br><br>Let us count the number of $\\alpha$-hydrogen atoms in each given alkene:<br><br>A. 2-Methylbut-2-ene: $(CH_3)_2C=CHCH_3$<br>Number of $\\alpha$-hydrogen atoms = $3 + 3 + 3 = 9$<br><br>B. cis-But-2-ene: $CH_3CH=CHCH_3$<br>Number of $\\alpha$-hydrogen atoms = $3 + 3 = 6$<br><br>C. 2,3-Dimethylbut-2-ene: $(CH_3)_2C=C(CH_3)_2$<br>Number of $\\alpha$-hydrogen atoms = $3 + 3 + 3 + 3 = 12$<br><br>D. Prop-1-ene: $CH_3CH=CH_2$<br>Number of $\\alpha$-hydrogen atoms = $3$<br><br>Since the stability of an alkene increases with the number of $\\alpha$-hydrogen atoms, the correct stability order is C > A > B > D.<br><br>Answer: C > A > B > D","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30434,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text { Degree of unsaturation } & =\\mathrm{C}+1-\\frac{\\mathrm{H}}{2} \\\\\n& =9+1-6=4\n\\end{aligned}$\nBenzene shows negative Baeyer's test\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/GlVDgXuDRgbvJesKMzC-dBAtUFPGvUVE6VECLty-sxo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nBoth compounds have four different non-aliphatic substitution sites.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30606,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f54d57f8-e832-414b-9861-9482a97454ef-image.png\" style=\"width: 100px; height: 110px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e50a4396-afce-49c3-ae47-cd78d61cb361-image.png\" style=\"width: 90px; height: 129px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/212d2ece-4093-4f7a-a77b-02518c550183-image.png\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 122px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5d0b1a6f-11af-42af-9b1b-25ac9be8b9a8-image.png\" style=\"width: 100px; height: 148px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e43d696b-ee4e-42f7-83a5-8f0e709f3288-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 170px;\" /></p><p><br />In&nbsp;a strong acidic medium acid-base reaction takes place so&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> group&nbsp;is converted to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover accent=\"true\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>+</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> group.&nbsp;Due to the formation of anilinium ion, significant meta nitroaniline&nbsp;is also formed.<br />The net reaction can be written as follows,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/49048840-55a7-49ed-a3d4-fe92f1cbf1b5-image.png\" style=\"width: 700px; height: 230px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (02 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30620,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5yR13DLgu-a5hHiPR2oLsmy_Awz0MOGsVz1R32mAGEc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/HK7ka0EYK0VbzAxFFGM0ZtaRvVBtblQkE_Mhgiunt18.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","$\\mathrm{HOCH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}=\\mathrm{CH}_2$","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7Pr1kg3JVoGoaI0ga7NmU4sYkLkm4AAzgm7zspJnMAM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/R1SOnyn_W5qcQe5XSVB9BZU9RQHQNvuV8H5ffezICeE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (26 May Online)","image":null},{"id":30519,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a53d125d-55cc-475c-93fc-6306396432f9-image.png\" style=\"width: 332px; height: 136px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f03cdcbf-04e4-47ac-a207-5a7f569d0e3e-image.png\" style=\"width: 342px; height: 144px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ae6945cb-0a96-42a6-a97a-3c420c8c465b-image.png\" style=\"width: 328px; height: 123px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2aa7c423-a2a6-4e68-8228-228ca1106d3c-image.png\" style=\"width: 334px; height: 135px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>In first step, bromination takes place which reacts with magnesium metal to form Grignard&#39;s reagent. This reagent generates very strong base which abstracts acidic hydrogen from methanol to produce benzene.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3121ac4d-db1f-4afb-bb9f-a76c0062b411-qnwnn.png\" style=\"width: 808px; height: 153px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30570,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3493b01f-9607-4cf6-ac9e-b35e0ccfe2e8.jpeg\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b0d6a546-cfd9-4194-ab54-28533ed30b46.jpeg\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/689bf4df-07f4-4f80-a8b2-e5de69a9f0fe.jpeg\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7f0e7c06-88d1-48a1-8900-fc140bf794cf.jpeg\">"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ecb04f41-7bed-401e-bc85-24047a0a69e6.jpeg\" /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1625301a-54d7-4e66-a7c5-7814510ace0c.jpeg\" /></p><p>Grignard reagents add to carbonyl compounds to give primary, secondary, and tertiary alcohols. Reacting a Grignard reagent with an aldehyde gives a secondary alcohol. Reacting a Grignard reagent with a ketone gives a tertiary alcohol.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null}]